Relationships are fantastic containers for growth and healing and there are certain types of growth that can only be done when you are beholden to another. But I don’t think that means it’s always a good time for a relationship.

Can you handle your own feelings AND those of another human? Can you process your own growth and ego work whether or not your partner is doing the same? Is it healthy or reasonable for you to commit to another when you can’t commit to yourself and your healing?

The thing is, you can get into any old shitty toxic relationship whenever you want but if your goal is to have healthy, committed partnership then yeah, sometimes being single for a stretch of time IS the right way to go before diving in. Relationships are work too.

I think if you are someone who was abusive in former relationships and is currently doing the work to change those patterns, you need to take your time before entering a new relationship. Some programs recommend that recovering addicts don’t date until certain milestones.

While I’m here for the idea that you don’t need to be fully healed or a finished product in order to be loved, I wholeheartedly disagree with the notion that there’s never a bad time to enter a relationship. There are absolutely times when a person should not.

Part of what I would hope this would accomplish is to unravel the damaging nature of diet culture and fatphobia—if you have to restrict calories, which literally fuel your body, in order to shrink yourself to feel better about your body, that’s a problem.

My ultimate wish is that we can change our language around bodies and diets the way we have around bodies and gender—instead of using words that come with moral connotations we simply state the facts. You aren’t “eating clean,” you are “restricting calories to achieve a result”

A diet is just what you eat. You don’t technically “go” on a diet, you simply change or restrict your diet. Clean eating is a myth and restrictive diets are 95% ineffective in the long term. They’re good for achieving short term results and that’s it.

Food is neither clean nor dirty, you are not clean or dirty for eating certain foods, there is no moral value to eating a vegetable over a bag of chips. What most refer to as “clean eating” is really just restrictive dieting, and that’s your choice but be real about your choices.
